This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for HIR.

## Core concept

An intermediate representation makes program meaning explicit enough for analysis and target lowering without carrying source syntax.

## Beanstalk boundary

HIR owns executable semantic state:

- control flow
- locals, places and regions
- local and cross-module calls
- checked numeric and cast operations
- runtime template construction
- target-neutral external call identities
- per-function link facts

HIR does not own:

- public semantic interfaces
- warnings or documentation
- compile-time page fragments
- entry metadata
- TIR
- unresolved generics or trait evidence
- project assembly

Those facts live in separate module artefact lanes.

## Rewrite focus

Explain control-flow graphs, temporaries, explicit effects, validation invariants and why one IR should not become a dumping ground for every compiler output.

Canonical details live in `docs/compiler-design-overview.md`.
